<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,358,526]" pageId="13" pageNumber="576">
Mites of this genus also inhabit quills of hummingbirds (Atyeo &amp; Gaud 
<number box="[961,1021,358,382]" pageId="13" pageNumber="576" value="1979.0">1979</number>
), and can be characterized by having solenidia Ï‰ 
<number box="[279,293,395,419]" pageId="13" pageNumber="576" value="1.0">
<emphasis box="[279,293,395,419]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="576">1</emphasis>
</number>
on tarsi I and II inserted subapically. This genus is so far monotypic, although Atyeo &amp; Gaud (
<number box="[1369,1427,394,418]" pageId="13" pageNumber="576" value="1979.0">1979</number>
) had mentioned that it contains numerous undescribed species. The species herein reported are clearly different from 
<emphasis box="[213,418,467,491]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="576">
Ptyssalgers 
<taxonomicName authority="Trouessart" authorityName="Trouessart" box="[351,418,468,491]" class="Arachnida" family="Dermoglyphidae" genus="Paralges" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Astigmata" pageId="13" pageNumber="576" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="major">major</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
(Trouessart), but is not described because no males and only a single female were found. (Collection data as in the new species described herein).
</paragraph>
